SIMPLE: reside
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reside
<hw>Re*side"</hw> <pr>(r?-z?d")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Resided</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Residing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧sider</ets>, L. <ets>residere</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets>
re- + <ets>sedere</ets> to sit. See <er>Sit</er>. ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To dwell permanently or for a considerable time; to have a settled
abode for a time; to abide continuosly; to have one's domicile of home;
to remain for a long time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the moated grange, <qex>resides</qex> this dejected
Mariana.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In no fixed place the happy souls <qex>reside</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have a seat or fixed position; to inhere; to lie
or be as in attribute or element.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In such like acts, the duty and virtue of contentedness doth
especially <qex>reside</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sink; to settle, as sediment.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To dwell; inhabit; sojourn; abide; remain; live;
domiciliate; domicile.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Residence</ent>⟦br⟧
